# Cloudflare Pages SPA fallback.
# Any path that is not a real static asset is served index.html (HTTP 200)
# so React Router can resolve client-side routes on hard-refresh, deep links,
# and email/OAuth callback URLs. Static files in /assets/* are matched first
# and served directly, so this rule never shadows real bundles.
# A MISSING hashed chunk must return a 404 STATUS — never a 200 with the SPA
# index.html body. During a deploy's propagation window an edge that does not
# yet have /assets/<hash>.js otherwise answers that URL with the SPA fallback
# (200, text/html); the browser then caches that text/html under the IMMUTABLE
# asset URL, so dynamic import() keeps failing and the app white-screens
# permanently — even after Ctrl+Shift+R (a plain reload cannot evict an
# immutable-cached entry). A 404 STATUS is never stored by the browser as the
# module, so the poisoning cannot happen and lazyWithRetry / the boot recovery
# reload cleanly. Existing chunks are matched as static files first, so this
# only ever affects a chunk that truly is not on this deployment.
# NOTE: destination is /index.html (which exists), NOT a dedicated 404.html —
# a real 404.html at the Pages root DISABLES the SPA fallback and makes every
# non-prerendered route (e.g. /app/*, the OAuth callback) return the 404 page
# instead of the app. Serving index.html with a 404 status keeps the SPA working
# while still giving a missing chunk a non-200 status.
# (2026-07-06 poisoned-cache incident + 404.html-broke-SPA regression.)
/assets/*    /index.html    404
/*    /index.html   200
